The purpose of this Traffic Analysis is to document the potential traffic impacts created by the
proposed Rochester Intermodal Transportation Center (RITC) on the surrounding roadway
network and recommend roadway improvements, if necessary, to mitigate adverse impacts
associated with the traffic generated by this facility.
The following discussion describes the traffic data used for this project and the methods used to
analyze existing and future conditions. This Traffic Analysis is based on the preferred
conceptual Alternative 2A and accompanying site plan from the Scoping Report.
The following design years are used in accordance with the NYSDOT Project Development
The growth rate used to calculate No-Build condition background traffic growth for this project
was 0.50% per year as per information provided by the Monroe County Department of
Transportation (MCDOT). This background growth rate is consistent with the background
growth rate that was used for the North / South Clinton Avenue St. Paul Street/ South Avenue
The project is located in the City of Rochester, Monroe County, New York. The proposed RITC
will be located at the same site as the existing Rochester Amtrak Station, which is located north
of the City of Rochester’s central business district on the south side of the Empire Corridor
mainline tracks (MP 371) at 320 Central Avenue. The site is bounded by Central Avenue to the
south, N. Clinton Avenue to the west, and Joseph Avenue to the east.
The existing Rochester Amtrak station has one ingress and one egress access on Central Avenue.
The conceptual site plan for the RITC shows that the proposed facility would essentially utilize
these two existing accesses on Central Avenue in much the same way as the existing Amtrak
accesses are designated; an entrance only access and an exit only access, with an on-site loop
road serving as a drop off area for passengers. A full movement access drive is proposed on
Joseph Avenue, north of Central Avenue which will provide access to the parking lot for the
facility. An internal road will connect the facility’s parking lot with the proposed RITC exit only
Central Avenue is the two-lane east-west roadway that borders the Amtrak Station to the south
and extends westerly of Clinton Street and continues easterly beyond Joseph Avenue. N. Clinton
Avenue and Joseph Avenue are two-lane north-south roadways that border the westerly and
easterly Amtrak Station property, respectively. No parking/ Taxi standing signs exist along the
south side of Central Avenue. No standing and 2-hour parking signs exist along the north side of

The existing posted speed limit on Central Avenue, N. Clinton Avenue and Joseph Avenue
within the study area is 30 miles per hour. Speed data was not collected to record actual vehicle
operating speeds. Vehicles were observed during traffic data collection and speeds appeared to
be low and appropriate for the context and design of the roadways.
Travel time estimates were not computed since this is not a major capacity project.
CHA collected turning movement counts from 4 pm to 6 pm on Tuesday, September 19, 2012
and from 7 am to 9 am on Wednesday, September 20, 2012, while school was in session. The
data was recorded in 15-minute increments by vehicle classification (cars, medium (Attachment
B single unit), heavy vehicles (Attachment B multi-unit) and busses) and included bicycle and
pedestrian counts. The traffic count data shows that the critical peak hour for the network
analysis of traffic operations are from 7:30 am to 8:30 am and from 4:30 pm to 5:30 pm. The
traffic volumes at each of the intersections were balanced for the network. The turning
movement traffic count data obtained by CHA is provided in Attachment C-2 of this Report and
are illustrated on Figure 1 of Attachment C-1.
When the counts were obtained, the west leg of the Central Avenue and N. Clinton Avenue
intersection was operating as a one-way eastbound roadway. There were one-way signs to this
effect as well and barricades to block the westbound direction of travel. There were also
overhead signs on the mast arms alerting motorists of the one-way flow of traffic. See photos 2
and 3 above. The City of Rochester indicated that the section of Central Avenue from St Paul
Street to N. Clinton Avenue was converted to one-way eastbound as part of a construction
project in the area during the summer of 2012. The City indicated that while there had been the
potential for this one-way flow of traffic to become permanent with the addition of angled
parking and an eastbound bike lane, Central Avenue will return to two-way traffic due to
opposition and lack of consensus from the stakeholders.
Therefore, the northbound left turn, southbound right turn, and westbound through movement
volumes at the Central Avenue and N. Clinton Avenue intersection from the Monroe County
Department of Transportation (MCDOT) Synchro models for the AM and PM peak hours were
used in conjunction with the CHA manual turning movement volumes to account for the
westbound volumes that could not be obtained during data collection due to the one-way closure.
The MCDOT Synchro model volumes are the most recent volumes that MCDOT has, which are
from a combination of sources covering different years of data.
Pedestrian counts were conducted at each study intersection concurrently with the vehicle traffic
counts and are included with the vehicle traffic counts in Attachment C-2. Pedestrian counts
during the weekday morning and afternoon peak hour showed a significant number of pedestrian
crossings. During the AM peak hour, there were 39 and 22 crossings at the Central Avenue with
N. Clinton Avenue and Joseph Avenue intersections, respectively. During the PM peak hour,
there were 24 and 22 crossings at the Central Avenue with N. Clinton Avenue and Joseph
Bicycle counts were also conducted at each study intersection concurrently with the vehicle
traffic counts and are included with the vehicle traffic counts in Attachment C-2. Bicycle counts
during the weekday morning and afternoon peak periods showed that during the AM peak hour,
there were 0 and 2 bicycles counted at the Central Avenue with N. Clinton Avenue and Joseph
Avenue intersections, respectively. During the PM peak hour, there were 7 and 2 bicycles
counted at the Central Avenue with N. Clinton Avenue and Joseph Avenue intersections,
respectively. The bicycle counts include bicyclists that used the crosswalks at each intersection.

page.text: The overall project consists of replacing the existing Rochester Amtrak Station with a new multi-
modal facility and replacing the existing single-edge low-level platform with an American with
Disabilities Act (ADA) compliant double-edge high-level platform to improve passenger train
operations. The project also includes: track and signal work in the vicinity of the station to
improve passenger rail operations; improved and secure parking facilities and accessibility; ADA
compliance; and streetscape improvements and intermodal connectivity to bus and non-
Phase 1 – New Rochester Intermodal Transit Center (RITC) and Track Work
• Demolition of the existing Amtrak train station building
• Demolition of the existing site infrastructure
• Construction of the initial Amtrak train station building
• Bridge access from the new building to the platform
• Track realignment, including new interlocks and signals
• Secured surface parking lot, including access drives and retaining wall
The second phase would involve intermodal expansion of the RITC and redevelopment with
improvements to the existing bus station. The third phase would include streetscape
enhancements and connectivity improvements among the rail station, bus station, and downtown
The Institute of Transportation Engineer’s (ITE) Trip Generation Manual, the industry’s standard
source for estimating trip generation, was not used to assess the trip generation for this project
since the Manual does not contain a land use category that is specifically representative of the
operations of this project. Therefore, the trip generation was estimated for the 2014 (ETC) and
2034 (ETC+20) Build conditions based upon existing and future potential Amtrak ridership
discussed in the High Speed Rail Empire Corridor Tier I Draft Environmental Impact Statement
Exhibit 2-23 of the TIER I EIS summarizes the Empire Corridor Amtrak Station Boardings and
Alightings. Based on that Exhibit, it can be summarized that approximately 1,282,560
Boardings and Alightings are associated with the Empire West Corridor. That Exhibit also
showed that the Rochester Station had 128,935 Boardings and Alightings for 2010. Exhibit 1-4
of the TIER 1 EIS indicates that ridership in the Empire Corridor has increased from 2002 to
2011 with approximately 1.4 million person-trips in 2011. This indicates that there was an
increase in ridership of approximately 9.2% from 2010 to 2011.
The Tier I EIS provides anticipated ridership numbers based upon five alternatives that were
evaluated in the EIS; the Base (“No-Action”) Alternative and four Build Alternatives (designated
as 90A, 90B, 100 and 125). The Base (No-Action) Alternative represents a continuation of
existing Amtrak service with some operational and service improvements and consists of eight
planned rail improvement projects funded under TIGER grants to address previously identified
capacity constraints. Under the Base Alternative, train frequency would remain unchanged from
the existing frequency; thereby maintaining the four round trips per day between Albany-
Rensselaer Station and Buffalo, with three of those trips continuing to Niagara Falls. With the
Base Alternative, in 2035, annual ridership is estimated to be 1.6 million for the Empire
Corridor. Therefore, the expected growth in annual ridership, for the Base Alternative is 0.6%
This 0.6% per year annual growth for the Base Alternative was applied to the 2012 No-Build
entering and exiting vehicular volumes at the Amtrak Station for 2 years and 22 years to obtain
the 2014 (ETC) and 2034 (ETC+20) Build volumes, respectively. These volumes are illustrated
on Figures 7 and 9 of Attachment C-1. With such a low annual growth rate, when applied to the
existing low entering and exiting AM and PM peak hour site volumes for 2 years, there is no
increase in site generated volume during these peak hours. There was a slight increase in traffic
associated with the RITC for the ETC+20 condition. Figure 4 in Attachment C-1 shows the AM
and PM peak hour site generated traffic volumes for 2034 based on the Base Alternative. Since
the annual growth rate is low, the analyses were performed using only the existing site accesses
Since the Base Alternative represents the lowest growth potential expected in the corridor, a
Build alternative from the EIS was also evaluated to determine the potential effect increased
annual ridership would have on the surrounding roadway network, assuming additional
improvements are made in the Empire Corridor. Since the 90A and 90B alternatives are similar
in the expected potential annual ridership by the year 2035 (2.3 million vs. 2.6 million,
respectively), the more conservative 90B Alternative was used for this Traffic Analysis. Based
on the 90B Alternative, the expected annual growth in ridership from 2011 to 2035 is
approximately 2.6% per year. Since these improvements will not be completed by 2014 (ETC)
for the RITC, this 2.6% per year annual growth from the 90B Alternative was applied to the
2012 entering and exiting vehicular volumes at the Amtrak Station for 22 years to obtain only the
2034 (ETC+20) Build volumes. These volumes are illustrated on Figure 10 of Attachment C-1.
The annual growth rate results in minimal additional site generated vehicular volume during the
AM and PM peak hours of analyses for the ETC+20 condition. Therefore the analyses were
performed using the existing site accesses for the 90B Alternative. Figure 5 in Attachment C-1
shows the AM and PM peak period site generated traffic volumes for 2034 based on the 90B
The origin-destination of traffic generated by the RITC was assumed to be consistent with the
traffic patterns of the existing Amtrak Station operations.

The operating conditions of transportation facilities are evaluated based on the relationship of
existing or projected traffic volumes to the theoretical capacity of the highway. Various factors
affect highway and intersection capacity, including traffic volume, speed, roadway geometry,
grade, number and width of travel lanes and intersection control. The current standards for
evaluating capacity and operating conditions are contained in the 2000 Highway Capacity
Manual (HCM), published by the Transportation Research Board.
TrafficWare’s Synchro, version 7 was used to analyze the intersections within the study corridor.
The delay times and Level of Service (LOS) were analyzed for each intersection approach and
for the overall intersection to identify the performance characteristics of the existing conditions

Since the 90B Alternative represents a worst case scenario for this Traffic Analysis, this
Supplemental assesses the potential additional impact the site generated traffic could have to the
Central Avenue and Joseph Avenue intersection during the AM and PM peak hour traffic
conditions for 2034 (ETC+20) assuming the following: a) all traffic entering the facility would
travel through the Joseph Avenue intersection, as opposed to using the proposed RITC entrance
only, b) the traffic exiting the proposed RITC driveway heading westbound would continue to
utilize this access, and c) the traffic exiting the proposed RITC exit only driveway heading
eastbound would utilize the new access on Joseph Avenue.
The existing LOS results from Synchro appear consistent with the observed queues and delays
The procedures describe operating conditions in terms of Level of Service (LOS). In general,
LOS "A" represents the best operating condition and LOS "F" represents the worst. LOS "D" or
better normally represents acceptable operating conditions during peak periods. Descriptions of
LOS and the associated performance measures set forth in the HCM 2000 are provided in
Standard design objective for signalized intersections is to achieve a LOS D or better on each
lane group in urban areas during peak hours (NYSDOT Highway Design Manual, Chapter
5.9.2). For unsignalized intersections, the LOS is only calculated for minor movements since the
through movement on the major street is not affected by intersection traffic control. However, it
is recognized that there are many competing objectives and considerations, especially in urban
areas, that may affect the desirability and feasibility of achieving this goal for peak hours. In
these cases, peak-hour LOS E or F on individual lane groups may be acceptable.
